</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC3F95AD433C372FF22F95AFAE1FE6B" blockId="47.[155,771,1761,1905]" lastBlockId="47.[819,1435,196,433]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">
<emphasis id="B9082548D433C372FF22F95AFED2F92C" box="[155,291,1761,1782]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Description:</emphasis>
The largest fragment is 1.0 ¥ 0.8 ¥ 
<quantity id="4C8454BFD433C372FF61F944FED7F8CF" box="[216,294,1791,1813]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" unit="cm" value="0.4">0.4 cm</quantity>
. Cormus formed of large, irregular and loosely anastomosed tubes (
<figureCitation id="1347E5DFD433C372FE55F8A5FDBFF8EE" box="[492,590,1822,1844]" captionStart="Figure 41" captionStartId="48.[142,220,1762,1781]" captionTargetBox="[195,704,198,1729]" captionTargetId="figure-337@48.[195,706,198,1730]" captionTargetPageId="48" captionText="Figure 41. Clathrina hirsuta sp. nov. A, photograph of the holotype (¥ 10). B, triactines. C, diactines at the surface. Scale bar = 100 Mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5432712" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5432712/files/figure.png" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Fig. 41A</figureCitation>
). Water-collecting tubes converge to form conical projections with an osculum. The surface of the tubes is hispid because of the presence of diactines and trichoxea. Cells with granules were not observed. The skeleton comprises equiangular and equiradiate triactines (
<figureCitation id="1347E5DFD433C372FB46FEBAFA91FECD" box="[1279,1376,257,279]" captionStart="Figure 41" captionStartId="48.[142,220,1762,1781]" captionTargetBox="[195,704,198,1729]" captionTargetId="figure-337@48.[195,706,198,1730]" captionTargetPageId="48" captionText="Figure 41. Clathrina hirsuta sp. nov. A, photograph of the holotype (¥ 10). B, triactines. C, diactines at the surface. Scale bar = 100 Mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5432712" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5432712/files/figure.png" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Fig. 41B</figureCitation>
) and very few tetractines. Actines are conical and straight, with a sharp tip. Diactines are fusiform and slightly curved (
<figureCitation id="1347E5DFD433C372FC2EFEE6FC09FEA9" box="[919,1016,349,371]" captionStart="Figure 41" captionStartId="48.[142,220,1762,1781]" captionTargetBox="[195,704,198,1729]" captionTargetId="figure-337@48.[195,706,198,1730]" captionTargetPageId="48" captionText="Figure 41. Clathrina hirsuta sp. nov. A, photograph of the holotype (¥ 10). B, triactines. C, diactines at the surface. Scale bar = 100 Mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5432712" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5432712/files/figure.png" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Fig. 41C</figureCitation>
). They are projected towards the exterior of the tubes. Trichoxeas are also present, perpendicular to the surface of the tubes.
</paragraph>
